  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Cannot thank the staff at the MRI department enough&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Louise&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;On Sunday 17th March I attended the MRI Department at the Queen Elizabeth University Hospital for brain scans.  I was extremely nervous and anxious, and suffer from claustrophobia and PTSD. 
I cannot remember the names of the staff as I was too anxious, but I cannot thank them enough.
They explained the whole process to me iin depth, and knowing if had a bad experience with the MRI Scanners at another hospital, the staff took the time to let me see the scanner and did not rush me in any way to get in. 
The staff allowed me to bring a friend in to help calm me down and stopped the scan to ease my distress. Not once did they rush me or make me feel like a burden. 
I really would like to thank all of the staff who I dealt with that day, particularly the radiographer and male healthcare assistant who attended to me. They were so kind, polite, respectful and helped me through the scans. They maintained my dignity at all times and made a very difficult time much easier for me. This experience has changed my view of hospitals and made me realise that people genuinely do care. They are a credit to your hospital. Thank you for such a positive experience.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
